Prague Stock Exchange plummets into a negative at the end of trading
After the morning's sharp slump, the Prague Stock Exchange corrected its losses.
Transactions with CEZ shares reached almost half of the daily daily trade.
The Prague Stock Exchange followed up its Monday slump right from the start of trading on Tuesday, falling by nearly six percent.
This time, the decline is due to the decline in shares on Wall Street.
We also have a reaction from the market to the outcome of the U.S. House of Representatives vote, which has refused to support a plan to stabilise the financial sector there.
Share Fall in Asia
Shares in stock exchanges in Asia experienced a dramatic fall on Tuesday, although the indices eventually erased some of the losses over the course of the day.
The Hang Seng stock exchange's index in Hong Kong was off nearly four percent in the course of trading, but later erased some of its losses and the downturn reduced to around 2.5 percent.
The Hang Seng China Enterprises index, which tracks the Chinese stock market movements in Hong Kong, fell 3.8 percent, with markets closed in Shanghai.
Stocks on the Sydney stock exchange were down more than five percent, but eventually fell to 4.3 percent.
The Taiwan stock exchange fell 3.6 percent, according to the country's index.
"The timing of the rescue mission in the US is uncertain and will affect financial markets worldwide," noted the head of Hong Kong's monetary policy authority, Joseph Yam.
Hong Kong, although part of China, determines monetary policy on its own, without depending on China's central bank.
Hong Kong's interest rates are at the same level as the United States.
According to Australian Prime Minister Kevin Ruddo, US lawmakers should return to negotiations and approve the proposal to support the financial system.
Otherwise, he said, there is a risk that other countries will feel the effects.
The Blood Bath of American Stocks
The U.S. House of Representatives on Monday rejected a plan to support the financial system, which was expected to spend up to $700 billion (nearly $12 trillion).
Lawmakers thus ignored President George Bush's call to support the plan.
According to Bush, the plan would address the root causes of the financial crisis and help stabilise the entire economy.
US stocks experienced a bloodbath on Monday, with major stock indexes marking the biggest fall in more than 20 years.
The Dow Jones index fell nearly seven percent, marking a similar decline as recently as 1987.
The index had been falling before the vote, but once it became clear that the bill had failed in the House, the index was in a free fall.
Congress backs down: US government may pump $700 billion into banks
The leaders of the U.S. Congress and the government of President George W. Bush agreed on a broader form of financial assistance agreement for the US financial system.
It will be voted on at the beginning of next week.
US lawmakers have made a breakthrough in talks to approve a rescue plan in the form of financial assistance for the US financial system of $700 billion (around £12 trillion).
However, it is not yet won.
Indeed, congressmen must complete some of the details of the agreement before they can publish and vote on the final form of the law.
The plan to support the financial system will be discussed on the floor of the House of Representatives on Monday.
On Sunday, the chairman of the House Committee on Banking and Financial Services, Barney Frank, told Reuters.
The Senate, according to sources, could probably vote on the plan on Wednesday at the earliest.
According to economists, the announcement that the bailout plan will be approved should be the first major psychological factor for a recovery in financial markets.
However, thereafter, it will be "cut-up" thanks to the complexity of the mechanisms to help markets achieve in practice.
Paulson: Plan must be effective
"We've made a lot of progress.
We have worked out our differences of opinion about what the shape of the package to stabilise the market should look like," Democrat Nancy Pelosi told Bloomberg.
According to her, the final vote could be reached later on Sunday.
Representatives of lawmakers met with US Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson overnight on Sunday to give the final shape of the government's fund.
This should buy back from financial corporations for non-sale mortgage assets that pull financial firms into heavy losses and threaten the stability of the entire system.
"We are on the brink of a definitive plan agreement that will work and must also be effective in the market.
We need to continue the recovery plan, but I think we're there," Paulson said.
Signal for Asian trading
The global financial crisis is hitting stock markets, which are falling sharply.
According to the non-Nazi Democratic Senator Harry Reid, legislators are thus trying to reach a final agreement in Congress on Sunday.
Indeed, they want to reassure investors before trading in Asian financial markets, which are the first in the time zone, where Congress's decision could affect Monday's trading.
But it is not yet clear with certainty when the two chambers of the US Congress will vote on the bill, nor whether they cannot strangle the negotiations at the last minute on a problem.
Lawmakers hope it will be passed in the next few days.
But the law will still undergo a number of changes.
The total amount earmarked for the assistance of the system is to be divided into two parts.
The initial $350 billion is to be available as soon as possible, as requested by President George Bush.
But Congress may block the release of the remaining amount if it is under the impression that the program is not fulfilling its function, in a run of an additional $100 billion and later a final $350 billion.
Bush praised the progress in negotiations
While the president may veto this decision, Congress may override his veto.
Despite these changes, however, the basic idea of the program, which was to obtain funds to buy back bad mortgage securities, the value of which has plummeted, because hundreds of thousands of Americans are unable to pay their mortgages, has remained intact.
"We've worked it all out.
The House of Representatives should be able to vote on the bill on Sunday and the Senate on Monday," Republican Senator Judd Gregg said.
US President Bush is also satisfied with the progress in the negotiations.
His spokesman, Tony Fratto, said that Bush was satisfied with Saturday's progress and appreciated "an auto-party effort to stabilise our financial markets and protect our economy."
Restrictions on golden parachutes
Senate Banking Committee Chairman Christopher Dodd, the head negotiator, said lawmakers had agreed to the responsibility for the money program, protecting taxpayers from losses, closing the breaks, the timing of the plan's financing.
The new law is also intended to limit the so-called golden parachutes for the directors of the company participating in the programme and sets up a committee to supervise the fund.
This should be run by the Treasury Department.
"We have worked very hard at this and have made great progress towards a deal that will work and will be useful for the market and for all Americans," said Paulson.
The plan also envisages assistance for homeowners who have problems with repayment.
The government should negotiate new repayments for the mortgages it will buy in order to reduce the monthly cost of instalments for borrowers and allow them to keep their houses.
Marek: Psychological help
The proposed plan is a good idea, according to Patrio Finance's chief economist David Mark, but it will be very difficult to implement.
"And that's because it is not known by what mechanism and at what cost the problem assets will be purchased.
This will be decisive for how the financial sector and the government will split the losses between them," Marek told news server iHNed.cz this week.
Whether the plan will be approved now or early next week is not that important, according to Mark.
"More importantly, this week's congressmen agree to support the plan and to consecrate it as soon as possible.
The psychological importance of the agreement on the approval agreement is the most important at the moment," Marek stressed.
The triumph of right-wing populists in Austria, together with 29 percent
The appreciable weakening of the two parties of the previous grand coalition and the significant strengthening of the right-wing populist parties were brought about by the early parliamentary elections in Austria on Sunday, according to the first preliminary results.
The Austrian People's Party (ÖVP) suffered particularly strong losses, with the position of the current president, Wilhelm Molterer, shaking gravely.
Conversely, the election leader of the Union for the Future of Austria (BZÖ), Carinthian Governor Jörg Haider is preparing a triumphant return to national politics.
According to preliminary results, the strongest party in the country of the Social Democracy (SPÖ) remains with 29.8 percent of the vote, but it loses 5.5 percent of the vote against the latest elections in 2006.
Worse still came the ÖVP, which loses almost nine percent of the vote with 25.6 percent.
These are the worst performances of both of these major parties in Austrian post-war history and, especially for the Peoples, who triggered early elections, a literally disastrous result.
As recently as the beginning of July, when the ÖVP withdrew from the coalition, the Peoples were well ahead of the SPÖ in their preferences.
But voters apparently punished them for letting the government fail.
Speaking in the first reactions to the results, there was speculation about the possible resignation of the party chairman and incumbent vice-chancellor, Wilhelm Molterer.
Observers believe this could happen as early as Monday at an extraordinary meeting of the party's bureau.
Such a development would probably facilitate the path to the still most likely way out of the election result, the renewal of the grand coalition of the SPÖ and the ÖVP.
However, given the strengthening of the two right-right populist parties - the Freedom Party (FPÖ), and the BZÖ, with 11 percent of the vote - the Social Democrats also voiced concerns about the replay of the November 1999 when the People's Party agreed with the populists (then the FPÖ was united, it was split from the BZÖ in 2005) in a joint government that even raised sanctions from the European Union.
This is clearly being determined by Haider, who has already said he is ready to work with any party and envisages a return to Vienna to national politics.
The Green Party was still in parliament, but it lost slightly and fell among the Austrian political parties from third to fifth.
Apparently, none of the other parties surpassed the 4% threshold and did not make it to parliament.
