In April 1999, we therefore rejected blood from people who had been in the UK for more than a month since 1980.
A few years ago, it was safely proven that the disease was transmitted through the blood.
This episode has shown us that it made sense to follow the principle of prudence."
In 1999, a much more accurate HIV detection technique appeared on the market: tests with the use of nucleic acid (NAT) that allow the presence of the virus itself to be detected in the donor blood, rather than the presence of the antibodies on which the tests were based were used before.
The NAT tests have made it possible to shorten the deaf period that occurs between the patient's infection and the moment when the first viruses can be detected by our techniques in the blood, the specialist explains.
We were able to shorten this period to less than a week.
We have significantly reduced the risk that some donors might be infected without even knowing it and without us being able to figure out.
These improvements have made it possible to significantly reduce the risk of obtaining AIDS through a blood transfusion.
The risk of getting blood from contaminated with HIV is now exposed to one person in 12 million.
"In other words, this means that 12 million blood products will need to be distributed before HIV anyone gets infected.
