These tissues are analysed, processed and frozen before they are stored at Héma-Québek, which also manages the only public bank of blood from the umbilical cord in Québek.
The umbilical cord, previously considered to be biomedical waste, abounds in blood-rich stem cells that can be used to treat serious diseases such as leukemia.
"A few weeks ago, we celebrated the deposit of our 1,000th sample of blood from the umbilical cord to the bank, and we expect to be taking over a thousand a year.
