Opinions - Orwellian discourse by Barrick Gold
In its September 17 edition, Le Devoir published a letter to Patrick J. Garver, executive vice president of the Canadian mining company Barrick Gold.
With the logic of Orwellian, it confirms that the world's largest gold producer has begun the prosecution of three authors and a poor libeled small publishing house in order to trigger a "transparent public debate" and is demanding six million of them.
If it is true that judges are independent and impartial, they do not judge truthfulness, especially in the case of prosecution for libel, but by law.
Not surprisingly, Garver is completely ignored by this crucial distinction.
Or is it the best way for Barrick Gold to have a public debate to break anyone who would dare to defend the opposite position?
Whatever the outcome of the process, the author and publisher of the book Noir Canada (Black Canada) will be forced to spend respectable sums to be ready to defend themselves and fight in a highly unbalanced fight with an army of attorneys supported by the almost bottomless pockets of the mining company.
Moreover, the tactics in these unbalanced struggles often consist in the degrading of the defendants in order to enforce conciliation proceedings that will be floundered by the opposing party and, moreover, by the subject of anyone who dares to pursue the matter.
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public debate, it should have presented its view to the matter to public opinion.
Contrary to what is happening in several countries where Barrick Gold operates, in Canada, the debate normally consists in an exchange of ideas, rather than in baton blows.
The mining company was therefore not enough to do so but to open its books, its documentation, and to establish a real debate through a newspaper, media, publications and funding of independent scientific teams that could shed light on the matter.
However, Barrick Gold does not seem to have any confidence in public opinion and rejects petitions and letters in support of the authors of the book Noir Canada.
Perhaps Garver could explain how he can demand a "public debate" while despising the views of the same public?
This word in the vice-president's world seems to refer to only bold-paying attorneys, and not all Canadians; that is a rather narrowed concept of the term.
In a democracy, even libelusers have the right to speak.
Barrick Gold does not understand - or does not want to understand - that the public, which supports the authors and publishers of Noir Canada, does so primarily because it rejects the brutal ways of mining society.
The public is ready to hear Barrick and consider the matter, but on the basis of a civilised exchange of arguments, not within what many perceive as a prosecution in which the defendant's mouth is to be clogged (in the prosecution of the "public debate," Barrick, incidentally, has just given an official notice to the authors of Noir Canada to officially inform them that they should stop using this term...).
Aside from the surreal speech of Garver, the prosecution initiated by Barrick Gold is a direct attack on the university's freedom of research and the search for truth, which are essential for any democratic society.
Overall, it denies the right to quote credible sources and to a debate about the facts and interpretations that itself form the basis of intellectual activity.
If, in a country like Canada, it is impossible to study and discuss topics that the rich firms of this world do not like without being prosecuted repeatedly prosecuted, who else will be able to do it?
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public and transparent debate, it could have been created if it had followed the scientific norms used by the authors of Noir Canada.
He has the right to answer.
The university environment to which we belong has long been able to manage debates and disagreements and resolve conflicts.
Barrick Gold's overreacting clearly shows that, despite what it claims, it has no appetite for a transparent debate.
This is a loss for the university world, as it is for the public debate in Canada, and it is time for governments to introduce measures to limit such a type of unjustified prosecution.
Operations to save Wall Street - Democrats and Republicans understand each other
Yesterday, the Bush administration and the leaders of Congress, both Republicans and Democrats, finally reached an agreement on the largest economic bailout plan since the Great Crisis of the 1930s.
A new version of the plan to use US$700 billion to hinder the financial crisis that has been clouding Wall Street for months now must be approved by both houses of Congress.
In particular, it envisages: better control of the chosen representatives over its application, new mechanisms to ensure the repayment of the public money imposed, new arrangements for capturing the number of houses seized for defaults, as well as the right to monitor the level of wages paid to executives of rescued firms.
US Chancellor of the Exchequer Henry Paulson, House Speaker Nancy Pelosi and Republican Representative at the Negotiating Table, Senator Judd Gregg, announced the good news a few minutes after midnight yesterday, following the end of the two-day negotiating marathon.
"We have made great progress and come to an agreement that is effective in the markets," said Bush administration official, Henry Paulson.
"Everything has been done so that the real economy and ordinary Americans are safe from the crisis currently underway on Wall Street," the Democrat explained.
"That's a crucial point: if we don't, the trauma, the chaos, and disruption of Americans' daily lives will be enormous," said Jad Gregg, a Republican.
Over the past few hours, the negotiations have taken to the maximum turn for fear of the effect of further failure on the investor's mood.
The time limit was the opening of the markets this morning.
Both candidates for the US president were invited to the negotiations later, and both were more likely to comment on the deal, but without rebuting their dissatisfaction, saying it had to be resorted to such an extreme solution.
Democratic Senator Barack Obama has added to the agreement on some of the measures, in particular to enable the owners of the residence to be retained, and the pay-as-you-go-run measures for the laboring state-resurited firms.
"When we ask the taxpayers to take special measures because of the irresponsibility of some people, there is nothing to congratulate themselves on.
However, these measures are necessary," he explained on the TV waves.
His Republican opponent, John McCain, who was questioned by another station on whether to vote for the proposed plan, replied, "I'd like to see the details, but I hope so."
"The rough traits I have read [proves] that it is something that we will all have to digest and use to move on.
Choosing inaction is simply unacceptable," he said.
The $700bn plan aims to buy back doubtful claims and risky and non-negotiable assets of US financial institutions with the taxpayer's money.
The plan comes after a 14-month crisis unleashing with the bursting of the housing bubble, which first led to the collapse of risky mortgage loans (subprimes), then transferred to other, more widespread forms of credit (PCAA) and resulted in a cash freeze on the banks and financial institutions.
The collapse of last week's first draft agreement is due to Republican members.
Ever since Democrats agreed to the government's guarantee for some of the "toxic" assets of companies in difficulty, but not to buy them, the belief is that the impasse is averted.
In an effort to approximate conflicting views in Congress, a measure has been added to stipulate that the government will be able to introduce new fees to help it get its deposit back if, as a result of the program, it has to take losses for five years.
The new plan envisages a first amount of $250 billion, to which an additional $100 billion can be added if the president deems it necessary.
The deposit of another 350 billion should be approved by Congress in a new vote.
In exchange for his help, Washington will acquire stakes in rescued firms that will pay him dividends in the event of a profit and which he will be able to resell when it is over.
The federal government will be able to delay the seizure procedures for the loans related to the loans covered by the plan, as well as set limits on the level of the valuation and compensation paid to the executives of the affected firms.
The architects of the plan would like to vote it in the House of Representatives as early as today and in the Senate on Wednesday.
Despite all the efforts made, it is not yet certain whether their plan will be green.
Yesterday, votes continued to rise against this project in both the Republican and Democratic camp.
"It's very obvious that Washington can't hear you," said Republican Scott Garrett, a member of the House Finance Commission, addressing voters.
"Yes, we have a serious financial problem.
Yes, there are solutions.
But earning money in the taxpayers is not the solution."
Democratic representative Brad Sherman, the moderator of a group of congressmen nicknamed the "Skeptics Committee," presents the whole thing differently, but comes to the same conclusion.
"The four hundred esteemed economics professors, among them the three Nobel laureates, wrote to us: we ask Congress not to rush too much and to examine closely which way to go," he said yesterday.
At the same time, it was reaffirmed in Europe that this crisis was a world crisis.
Following the end of the extraordinary meeting, the three Benelux countries announced the partial nationalisation of Fortis, the banking group, for €11.2 billion ($16.3 billion).
The intervention of the governments of Belgium, the Netherlands and Luxembourg became necessary after the French bank BNP Paribas announced that it was withdrawing from the purchase of its competitor, which is on the verge of collapse since it lost 2 billion euros ($2.9 billion) as a result of a crisis in risky real estate loans in the United States.
Fortis employs 85,000 people, is one of Europe's top 20 banks and the top ten insurers.
"We will not lose this money," Dutch Finance Minister Wouter Bos said yesterday.
"In return, we get the right to vote in the bank and influence.
And that's what savers and households in these precarious times can appreciate."
On the other side of the Channel, the British government, meanwhile, appears to have begun nationalizing another bank affected by the financial crisis.
According to the English press, the government was to take over all existing loans from the bank Bradford and Bringley, of which more than $41 billion ($75.5 billion) were loans to buy real estate.
According to its announcement yesterday, the branches and client accounts of the British bank will be purchased by the Spanish bank, the Spanish bank Santander.
Bradford and Bringley will be the second bank after Northern Rock, which the British government has had to nationalise since the start of the financial crisis.
