The psychology of trumping: why are we spending more money?
At auctions, customers are willing to spend more money, overestimate the goods.
The neurological and economic foundations of this well-known - and seemingly irrational - behavior have been uncovered by researchers in the field of neurology and economics at the University of New York University.
According to their study, published in the journal Science, people don't want to lag behind in the eBay auction-type competition, so they'd rather pay too high a price.
The research, using an experimental auction, attempted to map the scheme of this "game" in the nervous system.
One group of volunteers grated, the other group participated in a mock auction, using the functional magnetic resonance molding method (fMRI) to examine the active areas of the brains of the test subjects.
In both games, the participants could have won the money, but in the game of the auction, the important element of which is to outmaneuver the other side, the whole found under the cerebral cortex, called striatum, began to work intensively in the loss.
This brain area plays a role in the "self-referricisation" mechanism of the nervous system, in addition to many other functions.
The unscrewing of the price is therefore possible, according to the researchers, to be explained by the effort to avoid the stride reaction of the striata.
To shore up their theory, members of the research team surveyed the economists' financial cross-cutting investigation.
In it, under different conditions, three groups were bidding against one partner.
The control group was simply told what the fair value of the product was, and they made bets.
In addition, members of the group were promised that if they emerged victorious, they would receive an extra $15 as a reward.
The third group, on the other hand, received $15 before the auction, but in the event of a loss its members lost that money as well.
The difference between the two groups was therefore all about the fact that one was emphasised by a win and another by a loss.
The members of the group playing "against the loss," of course, were willing to go higher than they were in a control and "victorious" group, which confirms the neurologists' hypothesis.
"These results cannot be deduced from any pre-existing economic theory.
For these have until now explained the phenomena observable at auctions with the joys of victory and the avoidance of risk.
It was only the neurological imaging methods that helped us resolve the contradiction between the two theories so that we have now come to a third explanation," said Andrew Schotter, a professor at the University of Economics at the University of Economics.
Hepatitis: when to see a doctor?
Approximately half a billion people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C infection, while in Hungary this chronic liver disease is listed among the main causes of death.
The number of domestic cases of hepatitis infection is estimated at one hundred thousand, but only 7,000 of them are being treated. The cause of this is that the sick often do not know they are infected.
The name hepatitis is a summary of the name for infectious liver damage caused by various viruses.
There are many similarities in their symptoms, characterised by inflammation of the liver and jaundice, but the agents of the disease and the diseases they cause are different from each other.
Hepatitis viruss are spreading in two main ways, depending on the originator of the disease: hepatitis A and E digestive tract (for example, infected with food, water), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses in blood and bodily fluids (sperm, poppory secretions, spit saline).
In any case, travellers should be protected by vaccinating A and B, and there is no vaccine against the C virus.
Symptoms of hepatitis A occur two to three weeks after taking infected food, usually accompanied by nausea, weakness, abdominal problems, urges to vomit.
The skin and the whites of the eye are then made of jaundice, the lightened stool and darkened the urine. The treatment can take two to three weeks.
Every year, a million people die worldwide from a more serious type of the disease, liver cancer and liver cirrhosis caused by hepatitis B.
The main reason is that only one in ten of the infected is being treated medically for.
hepatitis C can also have very serious consequences: if not treated, it can lead to liver cirrhosis or liver cancer.
Most of the infected do not even know about their illness, the genres of the disease are being destroyed by the liver cells insidiously, and so the first symptoms do not come in many cases until 20-30 years.
That is why early prevention, the implementation of regular depistage, is very important.
In three groups, the disease occurs a lot more frequently than on average: between people who had a blood transfusion before 1991, between drug users and people with tattoos.
Currently, the projected global number of individuals infected with the chronic hepatitis C virus is 200 million.
As the disease can already be demonstrated by a routine laboratory examination, a person should contact his or her general practitioner if he or shears any sign of unknown origin.
When detected early, the disease is treatable, the virus can be removed from the body, preventing contagion and preventing cancer from developing.
September 30 is the world day of hepatitis, which was organised by the organisations with the sufferers for the first time globally in 2004.
It aims to draw attention to chronic liver inflammation caused by these viruses, the causes of its occurrence and the importance of early detection of the disease.
