What would be the best method of developing technologies capable of preventing collision, if not imitaten, of obstacle detectors occurring in the world of nature?
For example, bees.
The initial strategic idea of a surprise project, presented at the CEATEC trade fair in Japan, was given to Nissan by the unmarginal engineers. It was about building a new generation of precipitation systems.
In collaboration with the University of Tokyo, Nissan has designed a biomimetic robotic management system of BR23C, a robotized minicar that is equipped with bee properties, with the ultimate aim of helping to create a system that can eliminate all collisions.
"During the flight, each bee creates its own oval-shaped personal space, which is actually very similar to our safety protective cover," explained Kazuhiro Doi, CEO of the brand for technology PR and R&D.
Composite eyes play an important role, allowing bees to bee in all directions in the field of view of more than 300 degrees.
To copy the function of the composite eye, the engineers reached for the idea of a laser telecomer.
This identifies the obstacles up to 2 metres before the BR23C in the field of view of 180 degrees, calculate their distance and sends a signal to the on-board microprocessor, which immediately transforms into a collision-mastering operation.
The barrier is picked up in a split second, then begins to imitate the bee's movements and turn the wheels needed to prevent the collision immediately change direction.
Unlike any existing system, this folding maneuver is in an absolutely instinctive way.
"If that were not the case, the robotic car would not be able to react quickly enough to avoid the obstacles," explains Toshiyuki Ando, head of the Mobility Laboratory and the Robotic Car Project.
It must respond instinctively and immediately, as this technology suits the most vulnerable and innermost layer of safety protective packaging within which the collision is currently considered inevitable.
The process must be reflected in what the bee is doing to avoid other bees.
This process must not take longer than the blink of an eye.
However, unlike bees, this movement cannot be directed up, down or diagonally, it can only be two-dimensional and only in the direction that can be turned the wheels.
Thus, instead of the endless options offered to the bees when avoiding, the robotic car was only applied to the possibility of rotating movement, acceleration and slowing.
The BR23C uses lithium-polymer batteries that are lighter and have a higher energy density, which means they have a longer lifespan than the lithium-ion variants.
According to Ando, the instinctive, intelligent response, not the ability to process, are important, much less data storage.
This mechanism must only be processed and responded to a few incoming signals per second.
There is no need for him to store and respond using an intuitive logic based on data from previous manoeuvres, so he is constantly using only a memory of a few kilobytes.
It does not need memorization with giga- or megaabyte capacity.
This is the first step towards developing instant evasive technology, which Nissan estimates could get into mass-produced cars within a decade.
Another application option may be a connection of the unit with the GPS satellite navigation system, which, after avoiding the path of the obstacle, would lead the motorist to the specified final destination.
